Citations
Date: 9/11/1852
Source: NZ Government Gazette
Author:
Vol / Page: V/26/165
Edition:
Quote:  ... a hole was dug ..., and a quantity of the soil washed, but without any visible satisfactory result ... [A] favourable indication was noticed at a bar in the creek, and a quantity of the gravel and earth removed, a panful was taken from about two feet below the surface and washed, it produced a number of scales of gold.
Notes: 1852 Nov 9 NZGG (Report of Sub-Committee on Recent Gold Discovery in the Coromandel District) V/26/165

Date: 0/0/1973
Source: Annals of Early Dunedin
Author: REED
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: At the bank I was interested seeing the gold being weighed ... The gold is what is called `scale', in little flat pieces, varying in size from a pin's head to a threepenny bit.
Notes: c1861 Mrs J.W.Stack in 1973 Reed Annals of Early Dunedin 15

Date: 0/0/1879
Source: Geology of the Provinces of Canterbury & Westland
Author: HAAST
Vol / Page: 84
Edition:
Quote: ... I instructed my men to dig for gold; we found, to use a technical expression, `the colour everywhere'. They were generally thin, small scales, often only slightly rolled, and could not, therefore have been brought any distance.
